			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2333">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was thankful for the February issue of <em>The Sun</em>. Suicide and mental illness are unpleasant subjects and therefore rarely explored. I was surprised to find my experiences, thoughts, and fears surrounding these taboo topics mirrored in Esther Ehrlich&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/2178">Spring</a>&rdquo; and Alex Mindt&rsquo;s story &ldquo;<a href="/article/853">Free Spirits</a>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Like Ehrlich, I observed the tenth anniversary of a suicide this past year. Just as Ehrlich hoped to learn something new about what her mother&rsquo;s death meant to her, I have struggled to understand what my boyfriend&rsquo;s death meant to me. It was helpful to share that experience with Ehrlich through her writing. I no longer felt so alone.</p>

<p>Alex Mindt&rsquo;s narrator in &ldquo;Free Spirits&rdquo; waits to see if he, too, will develop the mental illness that afflicts his father. Likewise, I waited throughout my twenties to see if I would develop my grandmother&rsquo;s schizophrenia. Like Mindt&rsquo;s character, I felt as if a part of me wanted to develop the illness, thinking it would somehow connect me to her, help me understand her.</p>

<p>It was my grandmother I was thinking of when I read Veneta Masson&rsquo;s poem &ldquo;<a href="/article/851">Her, Rising</a>.&rdquo; I have imagined that my grandmother may still surface within me in other ways besides mental illness &mdash; perhaps in the way I smile, or enjoy a Heath candy bar, her favorite.</p>

<p>More often than I would like, I experience a nagging melancholy. It says, &ldquo;You are different. No one could possibly understand you.&rdquo; It is a feeling of isolation, of being cut off from a community. <em>The Sun</em> assuages that feeling for me and quiets that voice.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jennifer Hanks<br>Merlin, Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

